<chapter xml:id="ch-04-morphology-and-word-structure" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Morphology and Word Structure</title>

  <objectives>
    <title>Learning Objectives</title>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Define morpheme and identify morphemes within words</p></li>
      <li><p>Distinguish between free and bound morphemes</p></li>
      <li><p>Apply morpheme identification rules to analyze word structure</p></li>
      <li><p>Recognize common affixes for each open word class</p></li>
      <li><p>Understand how English builds new words through productive patterns</p></li>
      <li><p>Use morphological knowledge to make strategic writing choices</p></li>
      <li><p>Evaluate when affixed forms versus descriptive phrases improve clarity and concision</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <section xml:id="ch-04-morphology-and-word-structure-sec-41">
    <title>Morphemes: The Building Blocks</title>

    <p><term>Morphology</term> is the study of word structure and word formation. The fundamental unit of morphology is the <term>morpheme</term>—the smallest unit of language that carries meaning. A morpheme is a collection of sounds (or letters, in writing) that expresses a thought or concept.</p>

    <p>Words consist of one or more morphemes connected together. Understanding how to identify and analyze morphemes gives you insight into how English builds its vocabulary and how speakers create and understand new words.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Free and Bound Morphemes</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Morphemes fall into two categories based on whether they can stand alone:</p>

    <p><term>Free morphemes</term> (also called bases or roots) can function as independent words. They carry the core meaning of a word.</p>

    <p>Examples of free morphemes:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>boy, girl, walk, happy, book, run</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><term>Bound morphemes</term> cannot stand alone as words; they must attach to other morphemes. Most bound morphemes in English are affixes—prefixes that attach before the base or suffixes that attach after it.</p>

    <p>Examples of bound morphemes:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Prefixes: <foreign>un-, re-, pre-, mis-, dis-</foreign></p></li>
      <li><p>Suffixes: <foreign>-ness, -ly, -able, -tion, -er, -ed, -ing</foreign></p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Morpheme Analysis Examples</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Let's practice identifying morphemes in words:</p>

    <p><q><foreign>Big</foreign></q> — One free morpheme</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>big</foreign> = free</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><q><foreign>Bigger</foreign></q> — Two morphemes</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>big</foreign> = free morpheme</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>-er</foreign> = bound morpheme (comparative)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><q><foreign>Unbelievable</foreign></q> — Three morphemes</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>un-</foreign> = bound morpheme (prefix meaning "not")</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>believe</foreign> = free morpheme</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>-able</foreign> = bound morpheme (suffix meaning "capable of")</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><q><foreign>Rewriters</foreign></q> — Four morphemes</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>re-</foreign> = bound morpheme (prefix meaning "again")</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>write</foreign> = free morpheme</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>-er</foreign> = bound morpheme (suffix meaning "one who")</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>-s</foreign> = bound morpheme (plural marker)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><q><foreign>Expectantly</foreign></q> — Three morphemes</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p><foreign>expect</foreign> = free morpheme</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>-ant</foreign> = bound morpheme (forms adjective)</p></li>
      <li><p><foreign>-ly</foreign> = bound morpheme (forms adverb)</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-04-morphology-and-word-structure-sec-42">
    <title>Common Morphemes by Word Class</title>

    <p>English uses bound morphemes productively to create words belonging to different word classes. These affixes are <term>productive</term>—English speakers use them freely to create new words. You've probably encountered <q><foreign>unfriend</foreign></q>, <q><foreign>unsubscribe</foreign></q>, and <q><foreign>retweet</foreign></q>, none of which existed thirty years ago. The patterns are so reliable that you could invent a word right now and other English speakers would understand it immediately.</p>

